Creation and Build of a Java Project Using Apache Maven 
Tasks: Creation of Maven Repository, Maven life cycle 
Outcome: artifactid:sample-app ‘version’ 1.0-SNAPSHOT. (jar file) 
 
Aim 
To understand the use of Apache Maven by creating a Java project using Maven archetypes, 
executing Maven lifecycle commands, and generating a JAR artifact with version 1.0
SNAPSHOT. 

Theory  
Apache Maven is a build automation and project management tool for Java applications. 
It uses a Project Object Model (POM) defined in pom.xml to manage project configuration, 
dependencies, and build processes. 
Maven provides a standard directory structure and a predefined build lifecycle that simplifies 
compilation, packaging, and documentation generation. 

Procedure / Steps 
Step 1: Verify Maven Installation 
• mvn –version 
• Confirms Maven installation and environment configuration. 

Step 2: Create Maven Project Using Archetype 
• mvn archetype:generate 
• Generates a standard Maven project structure using online templates. 

Step 3: Select Archetype 
• Enter filter: 2309 
• Choose number: 9 
• Selects a basic Java application archetype with compiler support. 

Step 4: Enter Project Details 
• groupId: com.bnmit 
• artifactId: sample-app 
• version: 1.0-SNAPSHOT 
• package: com.bnmit 
• These uniquely identify the Maven project and define artifact naming. 

Step 5: Verify Project Creation 
• Check current directory for: sample-app 
Step 6: Verify Local Maven Repository 
• \.m2 folder → Maven stores downloaded dependencies locally to avoid repeated 
downloads. 

Step 7: Build the Project 
• cd sample-app 
• mvn package 
• Compiles source code and packages it into a JAR inside the target directory. 

Step 8: Clean the Project 
• mvn clean → Deletes the target directory to remove previous build artifacts. 

Step 9: Generate Project Documentation 
• mvn site → Generates HTML project documentation in target/site. 
Modification and Execution of Java Application 

Step 10: Modify Source Code 
• Navigate to: sample-app/src/main/java/com/bnmit/ 
• Replace App.java content with BankService code. 
• Demonstrates custom application execution using Maven 
• Rename Java File: App.java → BankService.java 

Step 11: Rebuild the Project 
• mvn clean 
• mvn package 
• Recompiles modified source and regenerates the JAR. 

Step 12: Verify Class Files 
• Check: target/classes 
• Confirms successful compilation of Java classes. 


